2 DATA WRANGLING

2.1 Transform variables

# Convert non-numerical variables to factor and convert "NA" to zero
training <- training %>%
  mutate(host_id = as.factor(host_id),
         neighbourhood = as.factor(neighbourhood),
         room_type = as.factor(room_type),
         last_review = ymd(last_review),
         reviews_per_month = ifelse(is.na(reviews_per_month), 0, reviews_per_month)
         )

2.2 Add a new variable

# Calculate the distance to city center
lat_center <- 41.8781 # Latitude of Chicago city center
lon_center <- -87.6298 # Longtitude of Chicago city center
training <- training %>%
  mutate(distance_center = distHaversine(
    cbind(longitude, latitude),
    c(lon_center, lat_center) ) / 1000) # Create new variable: distance_center (Unit: km)

2.3 Handle outliers

# Handling outliers using the IQR technique
cols <- c("availability_365", "price", "reviews_per_month", 
          "number_of_reviews", "minimum_nights", "calculated_host_listings_count","distance_center")

bounds <- list()
for (i in cols) {
  Q1 <- quantile(training[[i]], 0.25, na.rm = TRUE)
  Q3 <- quantile(training[[i]], 0.75, na.rm = TRUE)
  IQR <- Q3 - Q1
  
  bounds[[i]] <- list(
    lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR,
    upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
  )
}
# Replace outliers by lower or upper bounds
  training_clean <- training
    for (i in cols) {
      lower_bound <- bounds[[i]]$lower
      upper_bound <- bounds[[i]]$upper
    
  training_clean <- training_clean %>%
    mutate(
      !!i := case_when(
      .data[[i]] < lower_bound ~ lower_bound,
      .data[[i]] > upper_bound ~ upper_bound,
      TRUE ~ .data[[i]]
      )
    )
}

2.4 Handle skewness with log transformation (if applicable)

# Check skewness
skewness <- training_clean %>%
  dplyr::select(where(is.numeric)) %>%
  summarise(across(everything(), ~ skewness(., na.rm = TRUE))) %>%
  pivot_longer(everything(), names_to = "var", values_to = "skewness") %>% 
  filter(skewness > 1) %>% 
  arrange(desc(skewness))
skewness
## # A tibble: 4  2
##   var                            skewness
##   <chr>                             <dbl>
## 1 number_of_reviews                  1.19
## 2 calculated_host_listings_count     1.18
## 3 reviews_per_month                  1.06
## 4 minimum_nights                     1.06
# Log transformation to reduce the skewness which is larger than 1
training_clean <- training_clean %>%
  # transform zeros to very small values close to 0 for log transformation
  mutate(calculated_host_listings_count = replace(calculated_host_listings_count, 
                                                  calculated_host_listings_count == 0, 0.00001),
         minimum_nights = replace(minimum_nights, minimum_nights == 0, 0.00001),
         number_of_reviews = replace(number_of_reviews, number_of_reviews == 0, 0.00001)) %>%
  # we don't log-transform reviews_per_month cause it's a ratio variable
  mutate(log_calculated_host_listings_count = log(calculated_host_listings_count), 
         log_minimum_nights = log(minimum_nights), 
         log_number_of_reviews = log(number_of_reviews)
         )

# Check skewness after log-transformation
training_clean %>%
  dplyr::select(starts_with("log")) %>%
  summarise(across(everything(), ~ skewness(., na.rm = TRUE))) %>%

# Correlation table
var <- c("price", "minimum_nights",  "log_minimum_nights", "number_of_reviews", "reviews_per_month", 
         "calculated_host_listings_count", "log_calculated_host_listings_count", "availability_365", 
         "distance_center")
corr_results <- corr.test(training_clean[, var], use = "pairwise")

r <- corr_results$r
p <- corr_results$p

# Convert matrices to long format
r_long <- melt(r)
p_long <- melt(p)

# Combine correlation and p-value data
heatmap <- left_join(r_long, p_long, by = c("Var1", "Var2"))
colnames(heatmap) <- c("x", "y", "r", "p")

# Create significance stars
heatmap$stars <- ifelse(heatmap$p < 0.001, "***",
             ifelse(heatmap$p < 0.01, "**",
             ifelse(heatmap$p < 0.05, "*", "")))

# Plot using ggplot2
ggplot(heatmap, aes(x, y, fill = r)) +
  geom_tile(color = "white") +
  scale_fill_gradientn(colors = rev(colorRampPalette(brewer.pal(9, "RdYlBu"))(200))) +
  geom_text(aes(label = round(r, 2)), size = 2.5, color = "black") +           # correlation values
  geom_text(aes(label = stars, y = as.numeric(y) + 0.25),                    # stars (offset upward)
            color = "black", size = 2.5) +
  coord_fixed() +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, hjust = 1),
        axis.title = element_blank()) +
  labs(title = "Correlation Matrix with Significance Stars",
       fill = "r")

4.1 Splitting data

set.seed(9)
cv_split <- initial_split(training_clean, prop = 0.75, strata = price)

4.2 Linear regression

# 1. Preprocess data (Recipe)
rec <- recipe(price ~ log_minimum_nights + number_of_reviews + reviews_per_month +
    log_calculated_host_listings_count + availability_365 +
    room_type + neighbourhood + distance_center, data = train) %>%     
  step_novel(all_nominal_predictors()) %>% # assign a previously unseen factor level to a new value
  step_lencode_glm(neighbourhood, outcome = vars(price)) %>%
  step_lencode_glm(room_type, outcome = vars(price)) %>%
  step_zv(all_predictors()) %>% # remove variables that contain only a single value
  step_normalize(all_predictors()) # scale predictors only

# 2. Specify model

lm_spec <- linear_reg() %>% 
  set_mode("regression") %>%
  set_engine("lm")

# 3. Create workflow

lm_wf <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(lm_spec) %>%
  add_recipe(rec)

# 4. Do cross validation / bootstrapping
# 5. Define values to be explored
# 6. Tune model

4.3 Ridge model

# 1. Preprocessing data (recipe)
ridge_recipe <-
  recipe(formula = price ~ availability_365 + log_calculated_host_listings_count + log_minimum_nights +
           number_of_reviews + reviews_per_month + neighbourhood + distance_center + room_type, 
         data = train) %>%
  step_novel(all_nominal_predictors()) %>% # assign a previously unseen factor level to a new value
  step_lencode_glm(neighbourhood, outcome = vars(price)) %>%
  step_lencode_glm(room_type, outcome = vars(price)) %>%
  step_zv(all_predictors())  %>% # remove variables that contain only a single value
  step_normalize(all_predictors()) # scale predictors only

# 2. Specify model
ridge_spec <-
  linear_reg(mixture = 0, penalty = tune()) %>%
  set_mode("regression") %>%
  set_engine("glmnet")

# 3.Create workflow
ridge_wf <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe(ridge_recipe) %>%
  add_model(ridge_spec)

# 4. Do cross validation
set.seed(9)
fold = vfold_cv(train, v = 10)

# 5.Define values to be explored
penalty_grid <- grid_regular(
  penalty(range = c(-3, 1)), # this range is log scale
  levels = 20
)

# 6. Tune model
tune_res_ridge <- tune_grid(
  object = ridge_wf,
  resamples = fold,
  grid = penalty_grid)

# 7. Fit data to model
best_penalty <- tune_res_ridge %>% select_best(metric = "rmse")
ridge_final_wf <- ridge_wf %>% finalize_workflow(best_penalty)
ridge_final_fit <- ridge_final_wf %>% fit(train)

# 8. Calculate RMSE in training data
RMSE_ridge_train <- augment(ridge_final_fit, new_data = train) %>%
  yardstick::rmse(truth = price, estimate = .pred)

4.4 Lasso model

# 1. Preprocess data (Recipe)
lasso_recipe <- 
  recipe( formula = price ~ availability_365 + log_calculated_host_listings_count + log_minimum_nights + 
            number_of_reviews + reviews_per_month + neighbourhood + distance_center + room_type, 
          data = train) %>%
  step_novel( all_nominal_predictors() ) %>% # assign a previously unseen factor level to a new value
  step_lencode_glm(neighbourhood, outcome = vars(price)) %>% 
  step_lencode_glm(room_type, outcome = vars(price)) %>%
  step_zv( all_predictors() ) %>% # remove variables that contain only a single value
  step_normalize( all_predictors() ) # scale predictors only

# 2. Specify model (setting mixture = 1 for Lasso)
lasso_spec <-
  linear_reg( mixture = 1, penalty = tune() ) %>%
  set_mode( "regression" ) %>%
  set_engine( "glmnet" )

# 3. Create workflow
lasso_wf <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe( lasso_recipe ) %>%
  add_model( lasso_spec )

# 4. Do cross validation
set.seed(9)
fold = vfold_cv(train, v = 10)

# 5. Define values to be explored
penalty_grid <- grid_regular(
  penalty(range = c(-3,1)), # that this range is log-scaled
  levels = 20)

# 6. Tune model
tune_res_lasso <- tune_grid(
  object = lasso_wf,   # Workflow object
  resamples = fold,  # CV resamples
  grid = penalty_grid  )     # Possible values we want to explore

# 7. Fit data to model
best_penalty <- tune_res_lasso %>% select_best( metric = "rmse" )
lasso_final_wf <- lasso_wf %>% finalize_workflow( best_penalty )

4.5 Regression Trees

# 1. Preprocess data (Recipe)
reg_tree_recipe <-
  recipe( formula = price ~ availability_365 + log_calculated_host_listings_count + log_minimum_nights + 
            number_of_reviews + reviews_per_month + neighbourhood + distance_center + room_type, 
          data = train) %>%
  step_novel( all_nominal_predictors() ) %>% # assign a previously unseen factor level to a new value
  step_lencode_mixed(neighbourhood, outcome = vars(price)) %>% 
  step_lencode_mixed(room_type, outcome = vars(price)) %>%
  step_zv( all_predictors() ) %>% # remove variables that contain only a single value
  step_normalize( all_predictors() ) # scale predictors only

# 2. Specify model
reg_tree_spec <- decision_tree() %>%
  set_engine( "rpart" ) %>%
  set_mode( "regression" )

# 3.Create workflow
reg_tree_workflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_model( reg_tree_spec %>% set_args( cost_complexity = tune())) %>%
  add_recipe( reg_tree_recipe )

# 4. Do cross validation
set.seed(9)
fold = vfold_cv(train, v = 10)

# 5.Define values to be explored
reg_tree_grid <- grid_regular( cost_complexity( range = c( -4, -1 )), levels = 10 )

# 6. Tune model
reg_tree_tune_results <- tune_grid(
  reg_tree_workflow,
  resamples = fold,
  grid = reg_tree_grid
)

# 7. Fit data to model
best_mtry <- select_best(reg_tree_tune_results, metric = "rmse")
final_reg_tree_workflow <- finalize_workflow(reg_tree_workflow, best_mtry)
final_reg_tree_fit <- fit(final_reg_tree_workflow, data = train)

# 8. Calculate RMSE in training data
RMSE_reg_train <- augment(final_reg_tree_fit, new_data = train) %>%
  yardstick::rmse(truth = price, estimate = .pred)

4.10 Predict for test data

Clean testing data

# Convert non-numerical variables to factor and convert "NA" to zero
testing <- testing %>%
  mutate(host_id = as.factor(host_id),
         neighbourhood = as.factor(neighbourhood),
         room_type = as.factor(room_type),
         last_review = ymd(last_review),
         reviews_per_month = ifelse(is.na(reviews_per_month), 0, reviews_per_month)
         )

# Calculate the distance to city center
testing <- testing %>%
  mutate(distance_center = distHaversine(
    cbind(longitude, latitude),
    c(lon_center, lat_center) ) / 1000) # Create new variable: distance_center (Unit: km)

# Handling outliers using the IQR technique
cols <- c("availability_365", "reviews_per_month", 
          "number_of_reviews", "minimum_nights", "calculated_host_listings_count","distance_center")

bounds <- list()
for (i in cols) {
  Q1 <- quantile(training[[i]], 0.25, na.rm = TRUE)
  Q3 <- quantile(training[[i]], 0.75, na.rm = TRUE)
  IQR <- Q3 - Q1
  
  bounds[[i]] <- list(
    lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR,
    upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
  )
}
# Replace outliers by lower or upper bounds
  testing_clean <- testing
    for (i in cols) {
      lower_bound <- bounds[[i]]$lower
      upper_bound <- bounds[[i]]$upper
    
  testing_clean <- testing_clean %>%
    mutate(
      !!i := case_when(
      .data[[i]] < lower_bound ~ lower_bound,
      .data[[i]] > upper_bound ~ upper_bound,
      TRUE ~ .data[[i]]
      )
    )
}

# Log transformation to reduce the skewness which is larger than 1
testing_clean <- testing_clean %>%
  mutate(
         calculated_host_listings_count = replace(calculated_host_listings_count, 
                                                  calculated_host_listings_count == 0, 0.00001),
         minimum_nights = replace(minimum_nights, minimum_nights == 0, 0.00001),
         number_of_reviews = replace(number_of_reviews, number_of_reviews == 0, 0.00001)) %>% 
  mutate(
         log_calculated_host_listings_count = log(calculated_host_listings_count), 
         log_minimum_nights = log(minimum_nights), 
         log_number_of_reviews = log(number_of_reviews),
         )
